{"title_page": "Frank Stock", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox Judge\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]] Mr Justice\n| name                = Frank Stock\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Gold Bauhinia Star|GBS]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]], [[Justice of the peace|JP]]\n| image               =  <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] -->\n| imagesize           = 150px\n| caption             =\n| order               = \n|office               = Non-Permanent Judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal of Hong Kong]]\n|term_start           = 2010\n|term_end             = \n| office2             = Vice President of the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Appeal of Hong Kong]]\n| term_start2         = 2009\n| term_end2           = 2014\n| office3             = Justice of Appeal of the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Appeal of Hong Kong]]\n| term_start3         = 2000\n| term_end3           = 2009\n| office4             = Judge of the [[Court of First Instance (Hong Kong)|Court of First Instance]] of the [[High Court (Hong Kong)|High Court of Hong Kong]]\n| term_start4         = 1992\n| term_end4           = 2000\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|df=yes|1945|06|15}} \n| birth_place         = [[Southern Rhodesia]]\n| nationality         =\n| spouse              =\n| relations           =\n| children            =\n| alma_mater          = [[University of Liverpool]]}}\n\n'''Frank Stock''', [[Gold Bauhinia Star|GBS]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]], [[Justice of the peace|JP]] ({{zh|t=\u53f8\u5f92\u656c}}; born 15 June 1945) is a Non-Permanent Judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal]].  He was until 2014 a Vice President of the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Hong Kong Court of Appeal]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Southern Rhodesia]] (now [[Zimbabwe]]), Stock received his education in the [[United Kingdom]]. In 1967, he graduated from the [[University of Liverpool]] with a law degree.<ref name=gia>{{cite web|url=http://gia.info.gov.hk/general/201004/08/P201004080178_0178_63680.pdf|title=Annex Curriculum Vitae|publisher=[[Government of Hong Kong]]|date=8 April 2010|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nIn 1968, Stock started his legal career as a [[Barristers in England and Wales|barrister]] in [[England and Wales]] where he was in private practice for 10 years. He moved to Hong Kong in 1978 where he served in the [[Legal Department, Hong Kong|Legal Department]] as a [[Crown Counsel]]. Within a year, he was promoted to Senior Crown Counsel, and by 1984, he was Principal Crown Counsel. Stock was called to the [[Hong Kong Bar Association|Hong Kong Bar]] in 1984 and [[Queen's Counsel|took silk]] in 1985.<ref name=\"2000news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200010/03/1003201.htm|title=Judicial Appointment|date=3 October 2000|publisher=[[Government of Hong Kong]] |accessdate=9 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1987 to 1991 he was the [[Solicitor General of Hong Kong|Solicitor General]]. In 1991, he left the civil service.<ref name=\"2009 news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200906/25/P200906250209.htm |title=Judicial Appointment |date=25 June 2009 |publisher=[[Government of Hong Kong]]}}</ref>\n\n==Judicial career==\nIn 1991, Stock sat as a [[High Court (Hong Kong)#Part-time Deputy Judges|Deputy High Court Judge]].<ref name=\"2000news\"/>\n\nIn 1992, Stock was appointed as a full-time judge of the [[Supreme Court of Hong Kong|High Court of Justice of the Supreme Court]] (which became the [[Court of First Instance of the High Court]] on 1 July 1997). From 1993 to 1995, he was Chairman of the Insider Dealing Tribunal. He was [[Judge in charge of the Constitutional and Administrative Law List (Hong Kong)|Judge in charge of the Constitutional and Administrative Law List]] from 1999 to 2000.<ref name=\"2000news\"/>\n\nStock was elevated to the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Appeal]] in October 2000.<ref name=\"2000news\"/> He was appointed as Vice President of the Court of Appeal on 7 July 2009.<ref name=\"2009 news\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=11&art_id=98060&sid=28186890&con_type=1|title=Top judge slams 'shotgun' challenges|last=Moy|first=Patsy|date=11 May 2010|newspaper=[[The Standard (Hong Kong)|The Standard]]|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> \n\nHe was appointed a Non-Permanent Judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201004/08/P201004080178.htm |title=Senior Judicial Appointments: Non-Permanent Hong Kong Judges of the Court of Final Appeal |date=8 April 2010}}</ref> From 2010 to 2014, he primarily sat in the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Appeal]] and heard a few cases in the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal]].\n\nHe retired from the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Appeal]] as a full-time judge in 2014, but remains a Non-Permanent Judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal]].<ref>[http://www.doj.gov.hk/eng/public/pdf/2014/sj20140605e.pdf Speech by Secretary for Justice on Stock's retirement.]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hkcfa.hk/en/about/who/judges/npjs/index_id_5.html |title=The Honourable Mr Justice Frank STOCK, GBS |publisher=[[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Stock was awarded the [[Gold Bauhinia Star]] by the [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|Chief Executive]].<ref>[https://www.gld.gov.hk/egazette/pdf/20141822e/egn2014182222.pdf \"G.N.(E.) 22\"] [[Hong Kong Government Gazette]] (No. 22 Vol. 18 (Extraordinary), 1 July 2014)</ref>\n\n==Quotes==\n\"Those of us who live in societies where the common law is entrenched, where there is in fact an independent judiciary, and where basic courtesies and freedoms appear to be extended between man and man, take these things perhaps for granted. There is a need for us as judges and as practitioners and as students, as governmental authorities and as a community at large from time to time not to make assumptions but to stand back, go back to square one and to examine fundamentals; to understand the Ciceronian truism that we must all be slaves to the law in order to be free.\"<ref>[http://www.hk-lawyer.org/en/article.asp?articleid=2416&c=115 Interview with Hong Kong Lawyer magazine, October 2014]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-prec}}\n{{s-before|before = [[Andrew Cheung]]<br/><small>''Permanent Judge of the Court of Final Appeal''</small>}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[Hong Kong order of precedence]]<br/><small>''Non-Permanent Judge of the Court of Final Appeal''</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Kemal Bokhary]]<br/><small>''Non-Permanent Judge of the Court of Final Appeal''</small>}}\n{{end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stock, Frank}}\n[[Category:Hong Kong judges]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean emigrants to Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong Senior Counsel]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gold Bauhinia Star]]\n[[Category:British Hong Kong judges]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)]]\n\n{{HongKong-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox Judge\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]] Mr Justice\n| name                = Frank Stock\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Gold Bauhinia Star|GBS]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]], [[Justice of the peace|JP]]\n| image               =  <!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] -->\n| imagesize           = 150px\n| caption             =\n| order               = \n|office               = Non-Permanent Judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal of Hong Kong]]\n|term_start           = 2010\n|term_end             = \n| office2             = Vice President of the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Appeal of Hong Kong]]\n| term_start2         = 2009\n| term_end2           = 2014\n| office3             = Justice of Appeal of the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Appeal of Hong Kong]]\n| term_start3         = 2000\n| term_end3           = 2009\n| office4             = Judge of the [[Court of First Instance (Hong Kong)|Court of First Instance]] of the [[High Court (Hong Kong)|High Court of Hong Kong]]\n| term_start4         = 1992\n| term_end4           = 2000\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|df=yes|1945|06|15}} \n| birth_place         = [[Southern Rhodesia]]\n| nationality         =\n| spouse              =\n| relations           =\n| children            =\n| alma_mater          = [[University of Liverpool]]}}\n\n'''Frank Stock''', [[Gold Bauhinia Star|GBS]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]], [[Justice of the peace|JP]] ({{zh|t=\u53f8\u5f92\u656c}}; born 15 June 1945) is a Non-Permanent Judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal]].  He was until 2014 a Vice President of the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Hong Kong Court of Appeal]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Southern Rhodesia]] (now [[Zimbabwe]]), Stock received his education in the [[United Kingdom]]. In 1967, he graduated from the [[University of Liverpool]] with a law degree.<ref name=gia>{{cite web|url=http://gia.info.gov.hk/general/201004/08/P201004080178_0178_63680.pdf|title=Annex Curriculum Vitae|publisher=[[Government of Hong Kong]]|date=8 April 2010|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nIn 1968, Stock started his legal career as a [[Barristers in England and Wales|barrister]] in [[England and Wales]] where he was in private practice for 10 years. He moved to Hong Kong in 1978 where he served in the [[Legal Department, Hong Kong|Legal Department]] as a [[Crown Counsel]]. Within a year, he was promoted to Senior Crown Counsel, and by 1984, he was Principal Crown Counsel. Stock was called to the [[Hong Kong Bar Association|Hong Kong Bar]] in 1984 and [[Queen's Counsel|took silk]] in 1985.<ref name=\"2000news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200010/03/1003201.htm|title=Judicial Appointment|date=3 October 2000|publisher=[[Government of Hong Kong]] |accessdate=9 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1987 to 1991 he was the [[Solicitor General of Hong Kong|Solicitor General]]. In 1991, he left the civil service.<ref name=\"2009 news\">{{cite web|url=http://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/200906/25/P200906250209.htm |title=Judicial Appointment |date=25 June 2009 |publisher=[[Government of Hong Kong]]}}</ref>\n\n==Judicial career==\nIn 1991, Stock sat as a [[High Court (Hong Kong)#Part-time Deputy Judges|Deputy High Court Judge]].<ref name=\"2000news\"/>\n\nIn 1992, Stock was appointed as a full-time judge of the [[Supreme Court of Hong Kong|High Court of Justice of the Supreme Court]] (which became the [[Court of First Instance of the High Court]] on 1 July 1997). From 1993 to 1995, he was Chairman of the Insider Dealing Tribunal. He was [[Judge in charge of the Constitutional and Administrative Law List (Hong Kong)|Judge in charge of the Constitutional and Administrative Law List]] from 1997 to 2000.<ref name=\"2000news\"/>\n\nStock was elevated to the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Appeal]] in October 2000.<ref name=\"2000news\"/> He was appointed as Vice President of the Court of Appeal on 7 July 2009.<ref name=\"2009 news\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/news_detail.asp?pp_cat=11&art_id=98060&sid=28186890&con_type=1|title=Top judge slams 'shotgun' challenges|last=Moy|first=Patsy|date=11 May 2010|newspaper=[[The Standard (Hong Kong)|The Standard]]|accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref> \n\nHe was appointed a Non-Permanent Judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal]] in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.info.gov.hk/gia/general/201004/08/P201004080178.htm |title=Senior Judicial Appointments: Non-Permanent Hong Kong Judges of the Court of Final Appeal |date=8 April 2010}}</ref> From 2010 to 2014, he primarily sat in the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Appeal]] and heard a few cases in the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal]].\n\nHe retired from the [[Court of Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Appeal]] as a full-time judge in 2014, but remains a Non-Permanent Judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal]].<ref>[http://www.doj.gov.hk/eng/public/pdf/2014/sj20140605e.pdf Speech by Secretary for Justice on Stock's retirement.]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hkcfa.hk/en/about/who/judges/npjs/index_id_5.html |title=The Honourable Mr Justice Frank STOCK, GBS |publisher=[[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Stock was awarded the [[Gold Bauhinia Star]] by the [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|Chief Executive]].<ref>[https://www.gld.gov.hk/egazette/pdf/20141822e/egn2014182222.pdf \"G.N.(E.) 22\"] [[Hong Kong Government Gazette]] (No. 22 Vol. 18 (Extraordinary), 1 July 2014)</ref>\n\n==Quotes==\n\"Those of us who live in societies where the common law is entrenched, where there is in fact an independent judiciary, and where basic courtesies and freedoms appear to be extended between man and man, take these things perhaps for granted. There is a need for us as judges and as practitioners and as students, as governmental authorities and as a community at large from time to time not to make assumptions but to stand back, go back to square one and to examine fundamentals; to understand the Ciceronian truism that we must all be slaves to the law in order to be free.\"<ref>[http://www.hk-lawyer.org/en/article.asp?articleid=2416&c=115 Interview with Hong Kong Lawyer magazine, October 2014]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-prec}}\n{{s-before|before = [[Andrew Cheung]]<br/><small>''Permanent Judge of the Court of Final Appeal''</small>}}\n{{s-ttl|title = [[Hong Kong order of precedence]]<br/><small>''Non-Permanent Judge of the Court of Final Appeal''</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after = [[Kemal Bokhary]]<br/><small>''Non-Permanent Judge of the Court of Final Appeal''</small>}}\n{{end}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stock, Frank}}\n[[Category:Hong Kong judges]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean emigrants to Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong Senior Counsel]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Gold Bauhinia Star]]\n[[Category:British Hong Kong judges]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)]]\n\n{{HongKong-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "CityPride", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJudicial career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Stock"}
{"title_page": "Donald Raleigh", "text_new": "'''Donald J. Raleigh''' is an [[United States|American]] scholar specializing in twentieth-century [[Russia]]n history.<ref>[http://history.unc.edu/people/faculty/donald-j-raleigh/ Bio]</ref> He is the Jay Richard Judson Distinguished Professor of History at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]. He obtained his BA degree from [[Knox College (Illinois)|Knox College]] in 1971, followed by MA and PhD degrees from [[Indiana University]]. He has written extensively on the [[Russian Revolution]], on local history (including two books on the [[Saratov]] region), and on Soviet [[oral history]]. He edited the scholarly journal ''Soviet (Russian) Studies in History'' and the monograph series ''The New Russian History''.\n\nMore recently, he has researched the life and times of Soviet leader [[Leonid Brezhnev]]. His 2011 book ''Soviet Baby Boomers: An Oral History of Russia\u2019s Cold War Generation'' was nominated for the [[Pushkin House Book Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.knox.edu/knoxinthenews/?p=1836 |title=Knox Alum Studies Russia\u2019s \"Cold War\" Generation |last=Peter |date=February 19, 2015  |website=[[Knox College (Illinois)|Knox College]] |accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''Soviet Baby Boomers: An Oral History of Russia\u2019s Cold War Generation'' (Oxford University Press, 2011) \n* ''Russia\u2019s Sputnik Generation: Soviet Baby Boomers Talk about Their Lives'' (Indiana University Press, 2006)\n* ''Experiencing Russia\u2019s Civil War: Politics, Society, and Revolutionary Culture in Saratov, 1917\u20131922'' (Princeton University Press)\n* ''Provincial Landscapes: Local Dimensions of Soviet Power'' (University of Pittsburgh Press, 2001)\n* ''Revolution on the Volga: 1917 in Saratov'' (Cornell University Press, 1986)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raleigh, Donald}}\n[[Category:American historians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Indiana University alumni]]\n[[Category:Knox College (Illinois) alumni]]\n", "text_old": "'''Donald J. Raleigh''' is an [[United States|American]] scholar specializing in twentieth-century [[Russia|Russian]] history.<ref>[http://history.unc.edu/people/faculty/donald-j-raleigh/ Bio]</ref> He is the Jay Richard Judson Distinguished Professor of History at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]. He obtained his BA degree from [[Knox College (Illinois)|Knox College]] in 1971, followed by MA and PhD degrees from [[Indiana University]]. He has written extensively on the [[Russian Revolution]], on local history (including two books on the [[Saratov]] region), and on Soviet [[oral history]]. He edited the scholarly journal ''Soviet (Russian) Studies in History'' and the monograph series ''The New Russian History''. \n\nMore recently, he has researched the life and times of Soviet leader [[Leonid Brezhnev]]. His 2011 book ''Soviet Baby Boomers: An Oral History of Russia\u2019s Cold War Generation'' was nominated for the [[Pushkin House Book Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.knox.edu/knoxinthenews/?p=1836 |title=Knox Alum Studies Russia\u2019s \u201cCold War\u201d Generation |last=Peter |date=February 19, 2015  |website=[[Knox College (Illinois)|Knox College]] |accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''Soviet Baby Boomers: An Oral History of Russia\u2019s Cold War Generation'' (Oxford University Press, 2011) \n* ''Russia\u2019s Sputnik Generation: Soviet Baby Boomers Talk about Their Lives'' (Indiana University Press, 2006)\n* ''Experiencing Russia\u2019s Civil War: Politics, Society, and Revolutionary Culture in Saratov, 1917\u20131922'' (Princeton University Press)\n* ''Provincial Landscapes: Local Dimensions of Soviet Power'' (University of Pittsburgh Press, 2001)\n* ''Revolution on the Volga: 1917 in Saratov'' (Cornell University Press, 1986)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raleigh, Donald}}\n[[category:American historians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Indiana University alumni]]\n[[Category:Knox College (Illinois) alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Raleigh"}
{"title_page": "Donald Lees Reid", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=December 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Donald Lees Reid\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Dalmellington]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| nationality = {{flagicon|UK}} [[Scotland|Scottish]]\n| occupation = Retired Policeman and [[Author]]\n| education =\n| spouse = Kathleen\n| children =\n| residence = [[Beith]], [[North Ayrshire]]\n| parents = James Reid and Mary Hose\n| relations = \n}}\n\n'''Donald Lees Reid''' BA (Hons) FSA Scot is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] author. He specialises in local and social history and has written books on the history of the Garnock Valley and Doon Valley, including the towns of [[Beith]], [[Barrmill]], [[Dalmellington]], [[Gateside, North Ayrshire|Gateside]], [[Kilbirnie]], [[Patna, East Ayrshire|Patna]], and [[Waterside, East Ayrshire|Waterside]]. He has resided in [[Beith]], [[North Ayrshire]] since 1986. A strong emphasis in the books is on the people and the social context of their lives.\n\nDonald was born and brought up in Dalmellington, the son of James Reid, a miner for 43 years, and Mary Hose.<ref name=k>Reid (2009), Page 72</ref> He retired from the [[Strathclyde Police]] Force in 1999 with the rank of [[Police Superintendent]].<ref>Reid (2010), Page 154</ref> In 1994 he was accorded the honour of being selected as Beith Citizen of the Year for his voluntary work.<ref>Reid (2010), Page 155</ref>\n\n==Authorship==\n# Reid, Donald L. (1994). ''Reflections of Beith and District - On the Wings of Time''. Beith High Church Youth Group.\n# Reid, Donald L. & Monahan, Isobel F. (1998). Yesterday's Beith. A Pictorial Guide. Beith : Duke of Edinburgh Award. {{ISBN|0-9522720-5-9}}.\n# Reid, Donald L. (2000). ''The Beith Supplement - The Story of Beith's Newspaper''. Beith : Duke of Edinburgh Award. {{ISBN|0-9522720-1-6}}.\n# Reid, Donald L. (2001). ''In the Valley of the Garnock. Beith, Dalry & Kilbirnie''. Beith : Duke of Edinburgh Award. {{ISBN|0-9522720-5-9}}.\n# Reid, Donald L. (2001). ''Old Beith''. Ochiltree : Stenlake Publishing. {{ISBN|1-84033-126-7}}.\n# Reid, Donald L. (2001). ''Old Dalmellington, Patna and Waterside.'' Ochiltree : Stenlake Publishing.\n# Reid, Donald L. (2002). ''Doon Valley Memories. A Pictorial Reflection.''\n# Reid, Donald L. (2003). ''Barrmill Jolly Beggars Burns Club - Reflections on a Diamond Jubilee.''\n# Reid, Donald L. (2004). ''Doon Valley Bygones.''\n# Reid, Donald L. (2005). ''Yesterday's Patna & The Lost Villages of the Doon valley.''\n# Reid, Doanld L. (2005). ''Robert Burns' Valley of Doon - An Ayrshire Journey Down Memory Lane.''\n# Reid, Donald L. (2006). ''More Old Beith.''\n# Reid, Donald L. (2009). ''Discovering Matthew Anderson. Policeman-Poet of Ayrshire''. Beith : Cleland Crosbie. {{ISBN|0-9522720-9-1}}.\n# Reid, Donald L. (2010). ''Beith, Barrmill & Gateside. Precious memories''. {{ISBN|978-0-9566343-1-3}}.\n# Reid, Donald L. (2012). ''The Lost Mining Villages of Doon Valley. Voices and Images of Ayrshire.'' {{ISBN|978-0-9566343-3-7}}.\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{refbegin}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{refend}}\n\n;Sources\n# Reid, Donald L. (2010). ''Beith, Barrmill & Gateside. Precious memories''. {{ISBN|978-0-9566343-1-3}}.\n# Reid, Donald L. (2009). ''Discovering Matthew Anderson. Policeman-Poet of Ayrshire''. Beith : Cleland Crosbie. {{ISBN|0-9522720-9-1}}.\n\n{{Portal|Scotland}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reid, Donald Lees}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of Scotland]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-writer-stub}}\n{{UK-nonfiction-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=December 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Donald Lees Reid\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| caption =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[Dalmellington]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place = \n| nationality = {{flagicon|UK}} [[Scotland|Scottish]]\n| occupation = Retired Policeman and [[Author]]\